  "prompt": "How do calculate the gear ratio?",
  "response": "To calculate the gear ratio between two gears, you need to know the number of teeth on each gear. The gear ratio is the ratio of the number of teeth on the driven gear (the one being turned) to the number of teeth on the driving gear (the one doing the turning). Here's how you can do it:\n\n1. **Identify the gears:**\n   - **Driving Gear (Input Gear):** This is the gear that provides the initial motion.\n   - **Driven Gear (Output Gear):** This is the gear that receives the motion from the driving gear.\n\n2. **Count the teeth:**\n   - Let \\( N_1 \\) be the number of teeth on the driving gear.\n   - Let \\( N_2 \\) be the number of teeth on the driven gear.\n\n3. **Calculate the gear ratio:**\n   The gear ratio (\\( GR \\)) is calculated using the following formula:\n\n   \\[\n   GR = \\frac{N_2}{N_1}\n   \\]\n\n   This ratio tells you how many times the driving gear must turn to make the driven gear complete one full rotation.\n\n**Example:**\n\nSuppose you have a driving gear with 20 teeth and a driven gear with 60 teeth.\n\n- \\( N_1 = 20 \\)\n- \\( N_2 = 60 \\)\n\nThe gear ratio would be:\n\n\\[\nGR = \\frac{60}{20} = 3\n\\]\n\nThis means that for every one rotation of the driven gear, the driving gear makes 3 rotations.\n\n**Interpreting Gear Ratios:**\n\n- A gear ratio greater than 1 (e.g., 3:1) indicates that the driven gear is larger than the driving gear, resulting in a reduction in speed and an increase in torque.\n- A gear ratio less than 1 (e.g., 1:3) indicates that the driven gear is smaller than the driving gear, resulting in an increase in speed and a decrease in torque.\n\nUnderstanding and calculating gear ratios is crucial for designing and analyzing mechanical systems, as it directly affects the performance and efficiency of the machinery.",
